creating a usual regression problem with runif, which generates random values using seed, here the variables will already have proper scaling

x<-runif(1000)
y<-runif(1000)

the relationship between z and the independent variables x and y is complex and non-linear(i.e.sine and cos)

z<-sin(3*pi*x)+cos(3*pi*y)+rnorm(1000, mean=0, sd=0.25)
plot(z~x)

plot(z~y)

dat<-data.frame(x,y,z)

Problem 2 :classification problem

rm(list=ls())
set.seed(29124)

x<-runif(1000)
y<-runif(1000)
o<-order(y)

the points will lie (noisily) in one class if inside a circle centered at zero with radius (0.5)^(1/2), and in another class if outside this circle

z<-ifelse(x^2+y^2+runif(1000, min=-0.15, max=0.15)>0.5, 1, 0)
plot(x~y, pch=y)

dat<-data.frame(x,y,z)

testing a glm (probit) model if it correctly classify these observations?

glm.mod<-glm(z~x+y, family=binomial)
glm.class<-ifelse(predict(glm.mod, type="response")>0.5, "red", "blue")
plot(x~y, pch=z, col=glm.class)
y.plot<-seq(from=0, to=sqrt(0.5), by=0.0001)
lines(sqrt(0.5-y.plot^2)~y.plot)

no, or at least not without some substantial modification (like polynomial terms). It draws a line through the circular boundary space.Which is very wrong.

so we see that inside the sample data set, the neural network model classifies the dataset quite well.

nn.dat<-prediction(nn)$data
## Data Error:  0;
nn.class<-ifelse(nn.dat[,"z"]>0.5, "red", "blue")
plot(x[o]~y[o], pch=z[o], col=nn.class)
y.plot<-seq(from=0, to=sqrt(0.5), by=0.0001)
lines(sqrt(0.5-y.plot^2)~y.plot)

this is overfitting.

next we check how does it do on test dataset

xx<-runif(1000)
yy<-runif(1000)
zz<-ifelse(xx^2+yy^2+runif(1000, min=-0.15, max=0.15)>0.5, 1, 0)

nn.class.p<-ifelse(compute(nn, covariate=data.frame(x=xx, y=yy))$net.result>0.5, "red", "blue")
plot(xx~yy, pch=zz, col=nn.class.p)
y.plot<-seq(from=0, to=sqrt(0.5), by=0.0001)
lines(sqrt(0.5-y.plot^2)~y.plot)

its performance is much better compared to GLM. We have almost perfect separation of the classes at the limit of what is possible given noise levels.
